Headlines.SeoHeadline: Mary Barra Marks a Milestone at GM, But Progress Stalls for Corporate Women
Headlines.Author: Sara Murray
Headlines.Headline: Mary Barra Marks a Milestone at GM, But Progress Stalls for Corporate Women

PARAGRAPH.#text: General Motors' decision to name Mary Barra as its next chief executive—and the first auto industry CEO—is being hailed as the latest breakthrough for women at industrial giants.Ms. Barra joins a host of other women atop formerly male-dominated firms, such as Lockheed Martin chief executive Marillyn Hewson, IBM chief Virginia Rometty and Hewlett-Packard chief Meg Whitman. And in a year that could arguably be called the year of the power woman--Wall Street veteran  snapped up the 85 Broads networking group, 's  turned her "Lean In" book into a bestseller and a global movement, and  took 's stock to heights not seen since 2006--it's a significant milestone given the history of the auto industry and GM in particular.But there are still few females in the top spot at Fortune 500 companies. Just 4% of Fortune 500 chief executives are female, and the frequently cited numbers tallied by Catalyst Inc., a nonprofit that tracks women's progress in executive roles, shows women appear to have hit a wall.Women held 16.9% of board seats at  500 companies this year, essentially flat from the 16.6% they held in 2012, according to a new study by Catalyst Inc., a nonprofit that aims to expand women's business opportunities. Not only has the number stayed flat during the last two years, it has barely budged over the past eight years.�

Headlines.Headline: Junk-Bond Spreads Tighten Further Even As Supply Blossoms

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--The extra yield that junk-bond investors demand over low-risk Treasurys dropped Monday to its lowest level since December 2007, even though issuers sold a record $11.7 billion of high-yield securities last week. The so-called risk premium on junk-bond yields slid to 580 basis points, or 5.8 percentage points, above Treasury securities with comparable maturities, according to the Merrill Lynch High-Yield Master II index. That is down nearly a full percentage point from a year earlier, when spreads hit record highs.

Headlines.Headline: US FCC Relieves Big Phone Cos Of Costly Data Requirements

#text: By Fawn Johnson Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--At the latest possible moment Saturday, the U.S. Federal Communications Commission gave a regulatory gift to five large phone companies, relieving them of costly requirements to provide the agency with certain internal company figures. The order goes far beyond a request from AT&T Inc.
to stop collecting data on customer satisfaction and service quality.
